quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
8,26,"And recall when you were few in numbers and deemed weak in the land, fearful lest people do away with you. Then He provided you refuge, strengthened you with His help, and provided you sustenance with good things that you may be grateful. {1}",footnotes:1:The reference to gratefulness in the verse is worthy of reflection. Bearing in mind the subject under discussion
8,27,"Believers! Do not be unfaithful to Allah and the Messenger, nor be knowingly unfaithful to your trusts. {1}",footnotes:1:'Trusts' embrace all the responsibilities which are imparted to someone because he is trusted. These might consist of obligations arising out of an agreement or collective covenant. It might also consist of the secrets of a group. It might also consist of personal or collective property
8,28,"Know well that your belongings and your children are but a trial, {1} and that with Allah there is a mighty reward.",footnotes:1:Excessive love of money and one's children often impair the sincerity of a person's faith and often lead man to hypocrisy
8,29,"Believers! If you fear Allah He will grant you a criterion {1} and will cleanse you of your sins and forgive you. Allah is Lord of abounding bounty.",footnotes:1:'Criterion' signifies that which enables one to distinguish between true and false; between real and fake. This is the shade of meaning conveyed by the Qur'anic term 'furqan'. If a man is God-fearing and tries his best to refrain from acts which displease God
8,30,"And recall how those who disbelieved schemed against you to take you captive, or kill you, or drive you away. {1} They schemed and Allah did also scheme. Allah is the best of those who scheme.",footnotes:1:Apprehending the Prophet's migration to Madina
8,31,"And when Our verses are recited to them, they say: 'We have heard. We could, if we willed, compose the like of it. They, are nothing but fables of the ancient times.'"
8,32,"And also recall when they said: 'O Allah! If this indeed be the truth from You, then rain down stones upon us from heaven, or bring upon us a painful chastisement.' {1}",footnotes:1:These words were uttered by way of challenge rather than a prayer to God. What they meant was that had the message of the Prophet (peace be on him) been true
8,33,"But Allah was not to chastise them while you are in their midst; nor was Allah going to chastise them while they sought His forgiveness. {1}",footnotes:1:This is a rejoinder to the challenge implicit in the above-mentioned remark of the unbelievers. In response it was explained why people were spared heavenly scourge during the Makkan period of the Prophet's life. The first reason being that God does not punish a people as long as the Prophet is in their midst
